1
00:02:16,118 --> 00:02:18,879
Is it possible that the water
has already killed them?

2
00:02:19,278 --> 00:02:21,159
Yes.

3
00:02:21,239 --> 00:02:22,719
Then what?

4
00:02:23,879 --> 00:02:25,599
If it doesn't work?

5
00:03:54,679 --> 00:03:56,118
Get them in the truck.

6
00:03:56,959 --> 00:03:59,079
Get the hoses in! Start pumping!

7
00:04:14,879 --> 00:04:17,679
Uh, I'm here to see
my husband, Vasily Ignatenko.

8
00:04:17,759 --> 00:04:20,118
He's a firefighter from Chernobyl.
I have permission.

9
00:04:20,319 --> 00:04:22,599
Chernobyl? I'm sorry, no visitors.

10
00:04:24,799 --> 00:04:27,118
Well, but Major...
Major Burov told me,

11
00:04:27,199 --> 00:04:28,478
-he said...
-No exceptions.

12
00:04:28,559 --> 00:04:31,239
Please. I've come all the way
from Kievskaya Oblast.

13
00:04:56,279 --> 00:04:57,919
Excuse me.

14
00:04:59,198 --> 00:05:00,599
Excuse me, excuse me.

15
00:05:00,679 --> 00:05:01,919
Who are you? What are you doing here?

16
00:05:01,999 --> 00:05:04,678
-I have a pass.
-You can't be here. It's not safe.

17
00:05:04,759 --> 00:05:06,559
I am here to see my husband.

18
00:05:06,639 --> 00:05:07,599
Vasily Ignatenko.

19
00:05:07,679 --> 00:05:09,119
He's a firefighter from Chernobyl.

20
00:05:09,198 --> 00:05:11,558
I know who Ignatenko is,
but you can't.

21
00:05:11,639 --> 00:05:13,559
I have permission. I've...

22
00:05:19,599 --> 00:05:22,599
You can see him for 30 minutes,
not a minute more.

23
00:05:22,679 --> 00:05:25,599
And you cannot touch him in any way.
Do you understand?

24
00:05:25,678 --> 00:05:27,839
-Yeah.
-Room 15.

25
00:05:29,518 --> 00:05:30,478
Thank you.

26
00:05:30,998 --> 00:05:32,798
-You're not pregnant, are you?
-No.

27
00:05:40,399 --> 00:05:41,998
I won't have
to give that to you.

28
00:05:42,079 --> 00:05:43,078
There they are.

29
00:05:43,478 --> 00:05:44,998
No, wait, wait, wait.
I haven't finished yet.

30
00:05:45,079 --> 00:05:46,159
No, no, he hasn't.

31
00:05:46,918 --> 00:05:48,199
Yeah, that's good.

32
00:05:50,959 --> 00:05:52,158
Yeah, better.

33
00:05:54,959 --> 00:05:56,599
Look who the cat dragged in.

34
00:05:59,118 --> 00:06:00,719
What did I tell you?

35
00:06:01,519 --> 00:06:03,759
There's no hiding from you,
is there? Eh?

36
00:06:06,958 --> 00:06:08,878
Easy, easy. It's okay.

37
00:06:08,959 --> 00:06:12,119
We're all okay. Yeah, we're okay.

38
00:07:19,238 --> 00:07:22,599
How, how, how did this happen?
Who gave them the idea?

39
00:07:22,678 --> 00:07:24,519
-Are you suggesting I did?
-Someone did.

40
00:07:24,598 --> 00:07:27,919
Someone decided
that the evacuation zone

41
00:07:27,998 --> 00:07:31,038
should be 30 kilometers,
when we know, here,

42
00:07:31,119 --> 00:07:33,758
cesium-137 in the Gomel district.

43
00:07:33,839 --> 00:07:36,398
-That's 200 kilometers away!
- It was decided.

44
00:07:36,479 --> 00:07:38,278
-Based on what?
- I don't know!

45
00:07:39,678 --> 00:07:43,439
Forgive me. Maybe I... I've just
spent too much time in my lab.

46
00:07:43,518 --> 00:07:45,119
Or maybe I'm just stupid.

47
00:07:45,879 --> 00:07:47,559
Is this really the way it all works?

48
00:07:48,639 --> 00:07:50,439
An uninformed, arbitrary decision

49
00:07:50,518 --> 00:07:52,678
that will cost who knows
how many lives

50
00:07:52,759 --> 00:07:56,479
made by some apparatchik?
Some career party man?

51
00:07:58,478 --> 00:08:00,479
I'm a career party man.

52
00:08:01,399 --> 00:08:04,078
You should watch your tone,
Comrade Legasov.

53
00:08:05,158 --> 00:08:06,278
Comrades...

54
00:08:07,279 --> 00:08:09,838
We have visual confirmation
that the fire is nearly extinguished.

55
00:08:09,919 --> 00:08:11,839
There has also been
a reduction in iodine-131

56
00:08:11,918 --> 00:08:13,838
and cesium-137 emissions.

57
00:08:13,919 --> 00:08:15,318
Good. Yes?

58
00:08:15,998 --> 00:08:18,719
But the temperature is rising.

59
00:08:18,799 --> 00:08:20,118
And, uh...

60
00:08:27,079 --> 00:08:29,838
There's a spike
in zirconium-95.

61
00:08:31,118 --> 00:08:34,199
It's from the cladding
on the fuel rods.

62
00:08:34,278 --> 00:08:36,519
Meaning what?

63
00:08:36,598 --> 00:08:38,879
The meltdown has begun.

64
00:09:15,918 --> 00:09:17,399
Get it off me!

65
00:09:19,918 --> 00:09:22,199
Get it off me!

66
00:09:29,398 --> 00:09:30,839
Stop moving!

67
00:09:30,918 --> 00:09:33,559
Get off him! You're hurting him!

68
00:09:34,358 --> 00:09:36,398
- You can't be in here.
- What's happening to him?

69
00:09:36,479 --> 00:09:37,878
Get out!

70
00:09:37,959 --> 00:09:39,638
You can't be in here!

71
00:10:20,838 --> 00:10:21,798
Yes?

72
00:10:21,878 --> 00:10:23,318
Comrade Shcherbina
is on the phone.

73
00:10:23,398 --> 00:10:24,719
Put him through.

74
00:10:26,119 --> 00:10:27,359
Well?

75
00:10:27,438 --> 00:10:29,078
The fire's nearly out.

76
00:10:29,158 --> 00:10:30,798
The bubbler tanks are being drained.

77
00:10:30,879 --> 00:10:33,718
We have successfully eliminated
the risk of a thermal explosion.

78
00:10:36,799 --> 00:10:37,759
And?

79
00:10:39,198 --> 00:10:40,759
The situation inside the core

80
00:10:40,838 --> 00:10:43,639
is deteriorating
faster than anticipated.

81
00:10:43,718 --> 00:10:46,438
The concrete pad will last
for six to eight weeks,

82
00:10:46,519 --> 00:10:49,439
but after that, Legasov estimates
a 50% chance

83
00:10:49,518 --> 00:10:51,158
that the fuel will breach the pad

84
00:10:51,238 --> 00:10:53,838
and melt down
into the groundwater itself.

85
00:10:54,759 --> 00:10:57,198
And where
does this groundwater go?

86
00:10:57,278 --> 00:10:59,238
The Pripyat River,

87
00:10:59,318 --> 00:11:02,118
which feeds into the Dnieper.

88
00:11:02,198 --> 00:11:05,438
The primary water supply for
approximately 50 million people,

89
00:11:05,518 --> 00:11:09,478
not to mention crops and livestock,
would be unusable.

90
00:11:09,559 --> 00:11:12,158
We're recommending we install
a heat exchanger under the pad

91
00:11:12,238 --> 00:11:15,199
to lower the core temperature
and halt the meltdown.

92
00:11:15,278 --> 00:11:18,199
And in order to do that,
I'm told that we will need

93
00:11:20,438 --> 00:11:24,119
all of the liquid nitrogen
in the Soviet Union.

94
00:11:26,478 --> 00:11:27,438
Oh.

95
00:11:28,478 --> 00:11:29,518
All right.

96
00:11:29,599 --> 00:11:31,119
Yeah, and of course,
we'll also need...

97
00:11:31,198 --> 00:11:32,438
Whatever you need, you have it.

98
00:11:32,518 --> 00:11:33,878
-That should be clear by now.
-Yes.

99
00:11:33,958 --> 00:11:35,479
-Anything else?
-Uh, no, no, no. Thank you.

100
00:11:35,558 --> 00:11:38,478
Yes. I'd like to address
the 30-kilometer exclusion zone.

101
00:11:38,558 --> 00:11:41,198
Wait, what?
Professor Legasov, is that you?

102
00:11:41,279 --> 00:11:42,479
What exclusion zone?

103
00:11:42,558 --> 00:11:44,518
Minor details, General Secretary.

104
00:11:44,598 --> 00:11:47,039
Um, Premier Ryzhkov
has determined that...

105
00:11:47,118 --> 00:11:49,398
If he determined, then he determined.

106
00:11:49,479 --> 00:11:50,838
Look, Professor Legasov,

107
00:11:50,918 --> 00:11:52,758
you are there for one reason only.

108
00:11:52,838 --> 00:11:54,839
Do you understand? To make this stop.

109
00:11:54,918 --> 00:11:56,079
I don't want questions.

110
00:11:56,158 --> 00:11:57,719
I want to know when this will be over.

111
00:11:58,119 --> 00:12:00,078
If you mean when will
Chernobyl be completely safe,

112
00:12:00,158 --> 00:12:03,199
the half-life of plutonium-239
is 24,000 years.

113
00:12:03,278 --> 00:12:06,318
So perhaps we should just say,
"Not within our lifetimes."

114
00:12:18,078 --> 00:12:19,878
I think you and I should take a walk.

115
00:12:20,398 --> 00:12:21,999
It's late. I'm tired.

116
00:12:23,038 --> 00:12:25,279
We're taking a walk.

117
00:12:31,478 --> 00:12:33,799
What is it you want? An apology?

118
00:12:35,518 --> 00:12:37,158
Not gonna sit back and...

119
00:12:38,999 --> 00:12:40,998
What will happen to our boys?

120
00:12:41,879 --> 00:12:44,199
Which boys? The divers?

121
00:12:44,278 --> 00:12:47,079
The divers, the firefighters,
the men in the control room.

122
00:12:47,758 --> 00:12:50,998
What does the radiation
do to them, precisely?

123
00:12:52,638 --> 00:12:55,158
At the levels
some of them were exposed?

124
00:12:55,238 --> 00:12:58,238
Ionizing radiation tears
the cellular structure apart.

125
00:12:59,159 --> 00:13:01,878
The skin blisters,
turns red, then black.

126
00:13:03,478 --> 00:13:05,879
This is followed by a latency period.

127
00:13:07,038 --> 00:13:08,838
The immediate effects subside.

128
00:13:08,918 --> 00:13:10,598
The patient appears to be recovering.

129
00:13:11,758 --> 00:13:14,038
Healthy, even. But they aren't.

130
00:13:15,598 --> 00:13:18,798
This usually only lasts
for a day or two.

131
00:13:21,198 --> 00:13:22,358
Continue.

132
00:13:23,839 --> 00:13:27,398
Then the cellular damage
begins to manifest.

133
00:13:27,478 --> 00:13:32,678
The bone marrow dies,
the immune system fails,

134
00:13:32,759 --> 00:13:36,278
the organs and soft tissue
begin to decompose.

135
00:13:36,358 --> 00:13:40,238
The arteries and veins
spill open like sieves,

136
00:13:40,319 --> 00:13:42,639
to the point where you can't
even administer morphine

137
00:13:42,718 --> 00:13:46,158
for the pain, which is unimaginable.

138
00:13:46,918 --> 00:13:50,039
And then three days
to three weeks, you're dead.

139
00:13:52,198 --> 00:13:54,358
That is what will happen
to those boys.

140
00:13:56,598 --> 00:13:57,918
And what about us?

141
00:14:01,198 --> 00:14:02,918
Well, we've...

142
00:14:02,998 --> 00:14:05,838
We've gotten a steady dose,
but not as much of it.

143
00:14:07,118 --> 00:14:08,878
Not strong enough to kill the cells,

144
00:14:08,958 --> 00:14:11,878
but consistent enough
to damage our DNA.

145
00:14:13,278 --> 00:14:15,918
So, in time, cancer.

146
00:14:16,438 --> 00:14:19,558
Or a plastic anemia. Either way, fatal.

147
00:14:22,198 --> 00:14:23,438
Well...

148
00:14:25,398 --> 00:14:30,798
In a sense, it would seem we've
gotten off easy then, Valery.

149
00:14:42,998 --> 00:14:44,718
I've seen them before.

150
00:14:50,518 --> 00:14:53,679
Now you know
why I wanted to take a walk.

151
00:14:53,758 --> 00:14:55,918
We can presume
the work site is bugged.

152
00:14:56,878 --> 00:15:00,758
And our rooms, even our bathrooms.

153
00:15:00,838 --> 00:15:02,918
They've been here the whole time.

154
00:15:02,998 --> 00:15:04,918
Of course, they've been here
the whole time.

155
00:15:06,118 --> 00:15:09,838
But if we're seeing them
out in the open now,

156
00:15:09,918 --> 00:15:12,479
it's because they want us to know.

157
00:15:52,638 --> 00:15:53,759
You've seen that?

158
00:15:56,118 --> 00:15:58,078
The fuel is melting
faster than we expected.

159
00:15:58,158 --> 00:16:00,358
I know. I have a plan.

160
00:16:01,078 --> 00:16:03,558
Heat exchanger, I hope.

161
00:16:03,638 --> 00:16:05,038
Yes.

162
00:16:08,118 --> 00:16:09,958
There's something I've wanted
to ask you, comrade,

163
00:16:10,038 --> 00:16:13,278
but I see you're already asking
yourself the same question.

164
00:16:16,878 --> 00:16:19,038
Why did it explode?

165
00:16:20,678 --> 00:16:22,878
I've worked the numbers over and over,

166
00:16:22,958 --> 00:16:26,398
presuming the worst possible
conditions in an RBMK reactor.

167
00:16:28,318 --> 00:16:30,838
And I always get the same answer.

168
00:16:30,918 --> 00:16:32,278
Which is?

169
00:16:33,638 --> 00:16:34,758
It's not possible.

170
00:16:35,918 --> 00:16:37,278
And yet...

171
00:16:40,238 --> 00:16:42,238
You're not going to solve this here.

172
00:16:43,838 --> 00:16:45,278
Not on paper.

173
00:16:46,918 --> 00:16:48,638
Everyone who was in the control room,

174
00:16:48,718 --> 00:16:50,998
Dyatlov, Akimov, Toptunov,

175
00:16:51,078 --> 00:16:54,438
they're all in Moscow,
Hospital Number 6.

176
00:16:55,318 --> 00:16:58,238
We need to find out exactly
what happened that night,

177
00:16:58,318 --> 00:17:01,638
moment by moment,
decision by decision.

178
00:17:02,998 --> 00:17:04,918
Go now while they're still alive.

179
00:17:04,998 --> 00:17:07,118
Talk to them.

180
00:17:07,198 --> 00:17:09,678
Because if we don't find out
how this happened,

181
00:17:09,758 --> 00:17:11,958
it will happen again.

182
00:17:14,838 --> 00:17:16,478
And, Khomyuk...

183
00:17:17,998 --> 00:17:19,558
Be careful.

184
00:17:43,118 --> 00:17:44,598
Well, fuck you!

185
00:17:47,438 --> 00:17:49,318
Hey, here's one, here's one.

186
00:17:49,398 --> 00:17:51,238
What's as big as a house,

187
00:17:51,318 --> 00:17:54,238
burns 20 liters of fuel every hour,

188
00:17:54,318 --> 00:17:56,078
puts out a shit-load of smoke
and noise,

189
00:17:57,238 --> 00:17:59,398
and cuts an apple into three pieces?

190
00:18:01,838 --> 00:18:05,158
A Soviet machine made to cut
apples into four pieces!

191
00:18:42,878 --> 00:18:45,238
- Who's in charge here?
- I'm the crew chief.

192
00:18:46,837 --> 00:18:49,918
I am Shadov,
Minister of Coal Industries.

193
00:18:49,997 --> 00:18:51,238
We know who you are.

194
00:18:53,358 --> 00:18:54,958
How many men do you have?

195
00:18:55,518 --> 00:18:58,878
On this shift, 45 here,
a hundred in total.

196
00:18:59,758 --> 00:19:02,598
I need all 100 men to gather
their equipment and get in the trucks.

197
00:19:03,798 --> 00:19:06,118
Do you? To where?

198
00:19:07,798 --> 00:19:08,958
That's classified.

199
00:19:15,398 --> 00:19:16,518
Come on, then.

200
00:19:17,078 --> 00:19:18,278
Start shooting.

201
00:19:18,718 --> 00:19:21,318
You haven't got enough
bullets for all of us.

202
00:19:21,397 --> 00:19:23,478
Kill as many as you can,
whoever's left,

203
00:19:23,798 --> 00:19:25,358
they'll beat the living piss
out of each of you.

204
00:19:25,438 --> 00:19:27,598
-You can't talk to us like that!
-Shut the fuck up!

205
00:19:28,718 --> 00:19:31,118
This is Tula. This is our mine.

206
00:19:32,118 --> 00:19:33,838
We don't leave unless we know why.

207
00:19:35,797 --> 00:19:36,838
Mmm.

208
00:19:40,838 --> 00:19:42,758
You're going to Chernobyl.

209
00:19:44,798 --> 00:19:46,318
Do you know what's happened there?

210
00:19:47,398 --> 00:19:49,318
We dig up coal, not bodies.

211
00:19:50,438 --> 00:19:52,638
The reactor fuel is going
to sink into the ground

212
00:19:52,718 --> 00:19:55,518
and poison the water
from Kiev to the Black Sea.

213
00:19:55,598 --> 00:19:56,878
All of it.

214
00:19:57,958 --> 00:19:59,397
Forever, they say.

215
00:20:01,438 --> 00:20:03,878
They want you
to stop that from happening.

216
00:20:05,198 --> 00:20:07,278
And how are we supposed to do that?

217
00:20:08,078 --> 00:20:10,598
They didn't tell me,
because I don't need to know.

218
00:20:12,478 --> 00:20:14,878
Do you need to know,
or have you heard enough?

219
00:20:54,438 --> 00:20:57,118
Now you look like
the Minister of Coal.

220
00:21:17,798 --> 00:21:19,158
Vasya?

221
00:21:20,638 --> 00:21:21,837
Vasya?

222
00:21:27,678 --> 00:21:28,838
No, no, no.

223
00:21:29,798 --> 00:21:31,557
They told you no touching.

224
00:21:32,038 --> 00:21:34,198
It's not safe.

225
00:21:34,278 --> 00:21:36,438
They touch you.

226
00:21:37,478 --> 00:21:39,318
If it's safe for them,
it's safe for me.

227
00:21:48,997 --> 00:21:50,757
Where are the others?

228
00:21:50,838 --> 00:21:52,598
They took them to a special room.

229
00:21:54,197 --> 00:21:55,758
They won't tell me where.

230
00:21:59,878 --> 00:22:00,958
Will you open the curtains?

231
00:22:02,398 --> 00:22:03,358
Hmm?

232
00:22:03,637 --> 00:22:04,958
Open the curtains.

233
00:22:08,877 --> 00:22:09,837
Ah.

234
00:22:26,677 --> 00:22:28,757
Please, tell me what you see outside.

235
00:22:29,798 --> 00:22:31,237
Tell me everything.

236
00:22:38,438 --> 00:22:39,398
Um...

237
00:22:41,117 --> 00:22:42,997
I can see the Red Square.

238
00:22:45,958 --> 00:22:47,038
And

239
00:22:47,878 --> 00:22:49,597
the Kremlin.

240
00:22:50,837 --> 00:22:53,878
Spasskaya Tower, the mausoleum.

241
00:22:56,238 --> 00:22:57,837
You see St. Basil's?

242
00:22:59,398 --> 00:23:00,837
Yeah.

243
00:23:00,918 --> 00:23:02,558
Ah.

244
00:23:02,838 --> 00:23:04,478
Yes, it's beautiful.

245
00:23:05,958 --> 00:23:07,837
I told you.

246
00:23:07,918 --> 00:23:10,558
I told you I'd show you Moscow,
didn't 1?

247
00:23:10,758 --> 00:23:11,797
Huh?

248
00:23:11,878 --> 00:23:13,798
Yeah. Yes.

249
00:23:19,517 --> 00:23:21,238
Thank you.

250
00:24:06,598 --> 00:24:09,157
I'm not eating that. It's shit.

251
00:24:09,957 --> 00:24:11,118
Get me something else.

252
00:24:12,437 --> 00:24:14,797
I'm not a nurse, Comrade Dyatlov.

253
00:24:14,878 --> 00:24:16,638
I'm a nuclear physicist.

254
00:24:17,558 --> 00:24:19,878
Well, then, Comrade Nuclear Physicist,

255
00:24:21,357 --> 00:24:25,678
unless you happen to have
a butter and caviar sandwich on you,

256
00:24:25,757 --> 00:24:27,998
you can get the fuck out of my room.

257
00:25:43,677 --> 00:25:44,877
What?

258
00:25:45,918 --> 00:25:47,438
I'm not good at this, Boris.

259
00:25:48,437 --> 00:25:50,197
The lying.

260
00:25:54,438 --> 00:25:56,837
Have you ever spent time with miners?

261
00:25:58,678 --> 00:25:59,957
No.

262
00:26:00,117 --> 00:26:02,638
